[6] Japan (Okinawa): index case imported
Date: Sat 21 Apr 2018
From: Tomimasa Sunagawa <sunatomi@niid.go.jp> [edited]


An outbreak of measles is ongoing in Okinawa Prefecture, Japan since 23 Mar 2018. As of 18 Apr 2018, 65 confirmed cases have been reported. The index case of the outbreak was a tourist from Taiwan in his 30s. He had travel history to Thailand from 1-4 Mar 2018, developed fever on 14 Mar 2018 while in Taiwan, and traveled to Okinawa by air on 17 Mar 2018. During his stay in Okinawa, he visited multiple sites including a crowded shopping mall and duty-free stores in Naha City, the capital of Okinawa Prefecture. He also visited several sightseeing spots in the northern area of Okinawa Prefecture through 19 Mar 2018. After being diagnosed with measles on 20 Mar 2018 by PCR, he has been isolated. D8 genotype virus was detected from his specimen.

According to the data provided by the Okinawa Prefectural Government (http://www.pref.okinawa.jp/site/hoken/eiken/kikaku/kansenjouhou/documents/masin300419.pdf, in Japanese), except for the index case, there are currently 64 cases (all confirmed by PCR), including an infant less than one year of age, all of Japanese nationality. About 70% of them are older than 20 years of age. While the earlier cases either had direct contact with the index case or were present at the same location as the index case, cases without an epidemiological link to a confirmed case are now being reported. The majority, and over 75% of the adult cases, had no or unknown vaccination history. So far, there have been no reports of fatal cases.

It is expected that the measles virus will spread among unvaccinated persons, including infants, over the coming period. Children in Japan are strongly advised to get vaccinated as recommended (the dose at one year of age and the 2nd dose before entering elementary school); in addition, all infants aged 6-11 months living in Okinawa with an increased risk of contracting measles are currently being offered an extra measles vaccine.

The Okinawa Prefectural Government is working closely with local clinicians and other authorities to respond to this outbreak and is reminding the public of the need for a very high measles vaccination coverage in the population (at least 95 percent with 2 doses of vaccine in children and young adults, respectively), to protect themselves, families and friends, and others in the community. The Okinawa Prefecture Government is also in close communication with both the National Institute of Infectious Diseases (NIID) and the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare to share information and prevent further cases. NIID is providing summaries of this outbreak and related events appropriately (https://www.niid.go.jp/niid/ja/id/655-disease-based/ma/measles/idsc/7990-measles20180419.html, in Japanese).

--
Tomimasa Sunagawa
National Institute of Infectious Disease
<sunatomi@niid.go.jp>

[ProMED thanks Tomimasa Sunagawa for this authoritative report on the status of measles in Okinawa and for identification of the importation from Taiwan (see below). - Mod.LM]

******
[7] Taiwan
Date: Sat 21 Apr 2018
Source: Focus Taiwan [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201804210018.aspx


A 2nd case of measles was confirmed to have been contracted at Linkou Chang Gung Memorial Hospital in Taoyuan, which has prompted the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) to label the case part of a disease cluster at the hospital.

The CDC confirmed 2 new cases of measles in Taiwan Sat [21 Apr 2018], an imported case from Thailand and a domestic case found at the Linkou hospital.

The man infected at the hospital is a male nurse who is suspected of having contracted the virus from a patient on 4 Apr 2018.

Given that just the day before the CDC announced the case of a 40-year old woman who also contracted measles at Chang Gung Memorial Hospital, the CDC has deemed this situation a disease cluster and has asked the hospital to come up with response measures.

The hospital has assembled a response team to contain the situation and is currently monitoring 980 individuals that have come into contact with the measles carriers there.

With the 2 new cases of measles, 22 confirmed cases of measles have been reported in Taiwan this year [2018].

[Byline: Chen Wei-ting and Kuan-lin Liu]

